The Higgs boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson has aroused some excitement last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model – our best or “least wrong” explanation of nature and the behavior of matter – but not yet observed empirically.
But for the physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics congress in Kyoto this week, but there is still a lack of data to be completely sure about it.
Still, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as there seems to be little risk of being mistaken, and let’s look at what it’s all about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that means that two objects cannot be present in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and do not try too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: the Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state", with this "state" largely consisting of some of their characteristics.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, known as Fermione, who are faithfully obedient to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, an evil band of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - definitely not this principle, which means that they can, in fact, be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which is absolutely amazing) these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
That is, when a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at exactly this place, roughly like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" for this boson to show.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, somewhat comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be frightened by a very large rock.
That's why a huge particle accelerator like CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - is required to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on its own in the refrigerator.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What can all this research be "good for", asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, they serve to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to study all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who are eagerly hoping that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and fill some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major deficiencies, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there were none.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle – who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous-stroke laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 – already told us that the laser was initially seen as more of a “lab game.”
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras worldwide and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it does mean that you can never really know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With its Committee on Dying in Dignity, Quebec has recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate needs to be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I did seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
“It’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table before a delicious lunch, he resignedly agrees to let himself be helped with the meal.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to cure my diarrhea, because it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this ailment.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man pees standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the ability of the person to accept a step backwards, he notes.
Because according to several people who work in palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these setbacks.
Patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overcrowded with so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who take care of them.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation."
But through the illness I really got to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I don’t have any desires in life anymore,” she says before she accepts being given a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, she is still expecting a final visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
At the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers provide personal care and assistance with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, a bed for palliative care is available for every 11,700 inhabitants.
That’s very little if you take into account that one day we’ll all die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or pepsi.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died over the course of the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help relatives and patients alike,” reports Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
In the Victor-Gadbois home there is no day like the other.
Alongside a 93-year-old old man enjoying the last family gathering in the yard and being well supported by his pillows while being pushed in his honor, a 36-year-old young man surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children tragically dies after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, that is, to care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Greater Montreal Palliative Home Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care that causes several physicians specializing in palliative care to look forward to the passage of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care personalities such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to transition to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without any measures being taken to relieve her.
I fear that patients want to die only because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of the worst prognoses sour up to the last day.
Hélène Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued heavy chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I would stop the treatment, she replied that she regretted that I gave up the fight, she said.
She told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not giving up on this desire after their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in the patient falling asleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we are not perceiving this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to fall asleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
