After Bitcoin’s price peaked at $30 in June 2011, it dropped to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as “the virtual currency with the greatest success”, “competitive with the dollar or euro” and “similar to traditional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that can be won or bought through games (and sometimes also exchanged back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, every time trade is controlled and handled by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously custodians of the ledger, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the account book of the public accounts distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege of adding that extra line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can effortlessly check whether it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay very fast twice (less than 10 minutes) with the same money for cheating, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other remains unlinked, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but divisible up to a hundred millionth, which leaves a certain amount of leeway...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing performance.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and the Bitcoin deposits stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol,” assures Pierre Noizat, who just introduced Paymium, which is a company for paying with real money and uses the network Bitcoin.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Major players such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega-concluding sale" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," said Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its Paytunia system is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper as a result.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented with the dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend where hierarchical systems are reconsidered in favour of more horizontally oriented systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
Incidentally, the ECB’s report proposes to re-evaluate the various risks that are now highly regarded in the event of the success of this currency.
We moved out of Afghanistan.
And after that?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain ownership of its territory and for the Afghan people to decide their future without expecting anything from us.
In particular, we have punished Afghan farmers by considering them terrorists.
And ourselves with our 88 soldiers killed, as well as the injured and devastated.
The Taliban consist of foreign extremists, former leaders who have fled to Pakistan, but often also of peasants who refuse an armed foreign presence, as in the time of the Soviets.
They want to defend their centuries-old and archaic traditions, even though jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks and Tajiks have joined them.
Tolerated, sometimes supported by local insurgents, the latter will no longer be there if Western countries become more discreet.
The withdrawal of the French troops from the base at Nijrab, which I observed from a hill planted with almond trees financed with French loans, was done properly.
The truck and tank convoys flown over by helicopters have reached Kabul without being attacked.
From the end of 2014, there will be no more influx of the Taliban into Kabul.
Since its irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996, conditions have changed.
At that time, Kabul was empty and the country was overwhelmed by war due to the fighting of the various rebellious groups.
Their seizure of power was then seen as a kind of liberation and a return to security.
Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of the peasants overwhelmed by the Al Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved to this day.
Former Mujahideen, the Afghan government and the current Taliban have a common desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
The most important figures of the anti-Soviet war came back to power in 2001.
They have turned into shopkeepers by confiscating government land to sell it as construction land to refugees from Iran and Pakistan, thus benefiting from massive American subcontracting.
They were in disrepute, and most of them were not themselves involved in the fighting.
As I have heard in the campaigns, people want a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave the country, as do those who have been able to take advantage of American donations: the capital flight is considerable.
Young people are fed up with war and its ideologies.
During their exile in Iran or Pakistan, they have had contact with the modern world, and have enjoyed its benefits.
About 65% of the population is under 25 years of age; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, which is a fifth of the total population.
In the cities, the state schools are full of girls and boys.
These young people, who do not want to return to the obscurantism of the former parties or to the corruption of certain leaders, will have to be provided with jobs.
All, including the armed parties, are obsessed with mobile phones; television with its Turkish series representing a modern world is watched everywhere.
An army is now in place.
Are the authorities under whose authority it will be held to be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already working to restore the militias in the province that will escape the power of the central government.
Afghanistan, the country of mountains with strong local identities, should have benefited from some decentralization on the example of Western nations, but by abolishing the office of prime minister, which existed since the 1964 constitution, the US wanted to make it a centralized state with strong presidential power.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially during the elections scheduled for April 2014.
However, his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and long before.
Industries have not been rebuilt, functional dams are not available and important irrigation systems have not been repaired.
Everything is imported; except for fruits and vegetables, nothing is produced.
Private initiative is given priority.
In a country destroyed by 30 years of war, state control of infrastructure would have been required.
The rumor has spread that Afghanistan possesses immense natural resources.
This further reinforces the impression that the Western countries were only there to seize it.
Without energy to process the iron or copper ore on site, or without means of transport for export over the mountains, mining is not possible.
The Chinese have almost left the copper mine of Mes Aynak, leaving the international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to make their excavations at the huge Buddhist site and remain the main employers of the province.
One day it will also be necessary for Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports are largely dependent, to reestablish normal relations.
The withdrawal of the French troops was completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation agreement provides for the continuation of traditional aid: girls’ and boys’ gymnasiums, French Institute at universities, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, a service of "civil-military actions" of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), which was discontinued in 2012, has carried out numerous non-profit work and measures for the rehabilitation of agriculture in dozens of mountain villages and had carried out by a small French non-governmental organization in order to try to win the "hearts and spirits" and achieve the impossible task of reconciling aid and offensive.
These works, which required numerous local workers, have helped to suppress the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increase of agricultural land.
What souvenir do we leave behind after military spending of two billion euros?
A much more modest budget will contribute to improving local living conditions, which are very hard in these valleys, often more than 2,000 meters high.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small-scale agricultural projects from municipalities in Kapisa province.
In order for farmers to free themselves from the uprising led by foreign groups, which they say is their own wish, the continuation of smaller, more well-controlled and directly affecting civilian aid would be necessary in their favour.
A Constitution with the Crushing Rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever with regard to the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unrestricted authority, it has decided to put everything on one map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted this plenary two additional months to complete its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has relied on a provisional text that has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "footstep the right".
Its proponents assure us that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time forcing the brothers to renounce their plans to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
It’s also a way for the president to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
After confirming in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 largely Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they felt they were unable to bring their views to fruition.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve the decision-making capacity, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were usually adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only disagreement of the day... was expressed at the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the clock of the Constitutional Assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, finally remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and their respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The liberals, who see this only as a propaganda stunt, are responding to “fake holiness.”
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place over other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which grants Al-Azhar University an advisory function, in particular with regard to verifying compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt’s specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because “those who are asked to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see in this the first signs of a theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are also nurtured by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
“At present, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but academics who have been partly trained in the French system,” said Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He acknowledges, however, that there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
In particular, reference is made here to the "Fiqh" [Islamic Jurisdiction, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to decide on it.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticized for the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue: the powers of the army.
In line with the request of the military, the examination of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no prohibition of civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights associations have called for.
The latter also share their fears about the text, which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The blasphemy is being maintained, and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Furthermore, there is no longer any article on the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the top five reasons to visit Israel.
Prostrate in front of the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the conversion of water into wine at a wedding ceremony, walking on the water, the quenching of the sea storm and fishing.
Here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries are in Jerusalem.
Believers here commit the Way of Suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, in the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave behind notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a trip to the heights
The ruins of the Masada fortress are the remains of the secret hiding place built by Herod the Great for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rocky wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else takes a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country in 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, where it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the mountain top.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
On only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There are ancient Qumr’an manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean Desert, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
It exhibits the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of visitors and bathers at the time.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most striking section is the Children’s Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
Upon entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And it sounds the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
Israel’s three main recreational areas lie on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not drop below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salt content and thus carries even non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt sol) and healing mud, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, sugary disease and to soothe stressed nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets lie in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city, the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
Fortuna is said to be the legend after all hold that touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre nowadays features evening concerts and operas.
Wishlist for tourists
When you go to Israel, don’t worry about your bad English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the journey is preferred not in euros, but in dollars, which can be changed easily in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city, you usually travel by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed tram and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stops that connects the lower city with the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground cable car.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including transfers for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is at rest.
And on Sunday morning the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you’ll have the choice of different dishes with pork and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (Falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
There are many well-nourished cats that stroll through the streets comfortably and unobstructed.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Cats like busy places and don’t say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bicycle rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Admission tickets to museums cost on average 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the lifting of the visa requirement on February 9, 2011.
'The Great and Powerful' Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on mandatory language testing for migrants, criminals are already trading with fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in the homeland.
On December 1, a law came into force that requires every migrant to take a test that certifies the Russian language.
So far, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail sector.
However, according to the Federal Migration Agency, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
It is not only necessary to take language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for obtaining and extending the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, Problems and Protection of Rights
The entire body of examination will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship of Peoples, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants are able to take the tests in all cities; already now more than 160 corresponding centers have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law came into force in the press: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the requirement to demonstrate language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, responding spokespersons of the Migration Authority, it is about reducing the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," said Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must already be protected before you leave.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical examination encounter problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who will put him under the guise of help in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of months of his own without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have many complaints from our immigrants.
"At home, you will be promised the One, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports will be taken and you will not receive the promised salary," confirms the head of the Headquarters of Employment Migration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Swaripov.
Don't scold, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that they not only cannot master the language of the target country, but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable elementary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
“It’s difficult without language skills,” they admit.
“You feel humbled and inferior.”
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only immigrants with legal status have to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no exam and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of the visiting workers continue to be illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Prohibited Access for Unauthorized Persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for a thousand and a half.
The employees of the Russian police know that our documents are for the most part counterfeit and we are not registered, and this results in cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
"Just don't shy away from the cost of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the migrants’ registration documents could be falsified.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Agency.
The counterfeit papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive these for nothing: every migrant who hoped to be able to avoid the tests in this way paid 7,000 rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs one worker migrant three thousand rubles.
There is agreement that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time they get time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered positions in areas where no active communication with people is necessary.
Home Office Ignores Illegal Arms Market
Proportion of legal weapons to crimes extremely low
The Russian Interior Ministry is planning a tightening of the gun law for private gun owners.
The authorities respond to recent events: wounded in shootings at weddings and seven killed in the shooting of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Winogradov.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was endorsed by the chairwoman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarovaya, and promised that the amendments to the gun law would soon be presented to the Duma.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter has been published on the Internet, the authors of which - representatives of various arms associations - call on the authorities to refrain from "senseless aggravation".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said criminal justice lawyer Vasiliy Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand offences were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using the black market.
At present, according to the writers, you can find any weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the distribution of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who served ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or the military, that is, weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez said.
On the second channel come illegal weapons that are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen from both the police armouries and directly from law enforcement officials.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military stockpiles.
In many military camps there were often explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military official said.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers are also making a contribution to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private armaments factories that cannot withstand international competition and therefore waste their weapons on the black market, such as in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Particularly many guns and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a production of its own, sometimes artisanal, and a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military official.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated how much each of the five channels has about to supply the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminal literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
Most of the illegal weapons come from the army and the legal protection authorities, according to investigators.
Half of all guns on the black market have come there because of the “blame of those responsible who have been involved in their work with weapons,” the report said.
According to the researchers’ data, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% come from theft in weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant for a non-named gun shop assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long since been bought by anyone since they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for dealers to procure supplies in a weapons warehouse.
A weapon, for example a TT pistol, is purchased via a flag.
The weapon is displayed and passed through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
“The police, of course, are aware of everything and therefore, if they are not able to comply with the plan to detect crimes, periodically make control purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons,” the sales consultant adds.
"Like in the luxury store"
Buyers and sellers most often find each other through acquaintances.
I had been looking at websites and blogs when someone noticed me and suggested that I come to the Begovaya station, where a person would be waiting for me to take me to a certain place where we could negotiate the price.
I only found out about the price of the gun there.
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such an acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
