In recent days, there have been massive protests across the U.S. against low wages in Walmart stores and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
Nor can anyone predict whether the protests will swell even further or if they will soon run out of breath again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organizations.
In addition to raising the modest wages of simple Walmart and fast food workers, the organizers of the protests are pursuing the goal of founding unions.
So far, this sector of the economy is hardly organized by trade unions.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, on so-called Black Friday, when sales took place in the United States, attracting millions of customers, sometimes leading to handcuffs.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of which there are 2.2 million worldwide, quit their work and, together with unions and left-wing activists, attacked chain branches whose target group are low- and middle-income people.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in Walmart stores are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many of the low-paying Walmart employees only shop at their own workplace.
The prices and range of goods made Walmart one of the largest companies in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell the goods so cheaply only because employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, for example missing forklifts or hand scanners.
Participants in the Black Friday protests called for wage increases and expressed anger that the contribution to the company’s health insurance had risen from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee earning $9.5 an hour could not afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from the University of California at Berkeley prove that if the company increased the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That’s about 1.1% more than they’re now donating to wages.
If Walmart were to completely transfer the wage increases to customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
That would be $12.39 a year for them compared to today’s overspending.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that there have been protests in only nine states and these have caused no losses to the company.
Black Friday lasted in its store from 8 p.m. on Thursday night to midnight the next day, and during that period Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, Walmart cash registers carried out nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
The company's spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the left-wing Huffington Post's website that a total of "less than five" Walmart employees quit the work and that the protest was just "another PR trick" by the union that organized the protests.
"Free checkout!"
The protests continued this week in New York City, where their target was not Walmart stores (which are not desirable in this progressive city and therefore non-existent so far), but McDonald's and other low-cost restaurants.
McDonald's says the company sells billions of servings, and yet you are not granted sick days, and you are not paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage under federal and New York law is $7.25 an hour.
In fast food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too strong, and on average, their simple employees in New York get $8.90 an hour.
No one deserves less than you in this expensive city.
How it is possible to get around in New York with so little money is incomprehensible to me.
There was a time when almost a quarter of all U.S. young people were behind the counter after school at McDonald’s, but the young people were still living with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw it as the main source of income or planned to stay there longer.
Now, in interviews with McDonald’s employees, I constantly encounter people complaining that they have to get along with this pay and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a commentary in the Wall Street Journal forum, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to have children if one does not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6.30 a.m. in front of McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue on Thursday, demanded that cashiers and chefs of fast-food restaurants receive a minimum wage of $15 an hour, which is more than a doubling of the current minimum wage.
They continued to call for the formation of unions in the fast food industry.
U.S. law prohibits corporate governance from standing in the way of this goal and warning or dismissing union members.
On the other hand, management does not make it easy for them.
However, the establishment of trade unions in the fast food industry is also difficult for objective reasons.
The most important reason is the high personnel fluctuation.
Dissatisfied
There were loud protests that day in front of many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The culmination of the protests was a meeting at noon outside McDonald’s in Times Square where some local Democrats spoke, including City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said, “McDonald’s says it sells billions of servings, and yet you are not granted sick days, and you are not paid for your honest work!”
The protesters were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that “we should jointly support the fast food workers so that they can receive a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity every New Yorker deserves!”
According to the New York Times, this was the largest action of its kind in the history of the U.S. fast food industry.
However, there were only a few hundred people there, far from all of whom are employed in the fast food industry, with tens of thousands working in New York.
It is not yet clear whether the spark of these protests will mobilize entire masses.
"The brain can only be moderately outsmarted so far"
The theme of augmented reality, popular with followers of modern technologies, has recently been commonly perceived by the lens of a special glasses.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed a corresponding patent.
In conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft lab in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, however, it becomes clear that the glasses were only a transit station for the company’s scientists.
It excites the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes touched as well.
However, we want to anticipate 5-10 years and foresee the radical changes of this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are an advance, and nowadays, no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else awaits us in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, much is still played out on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output so far not decisive.
We try to change that, working on real three-dimensional representation systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could complement the real world much easier with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of these silly virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s popular, but isn’t it overvalued?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone around you about your actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the field of object management in public places, we worked on a project where we experimented with short and short rather than expansive gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but theoretically it could be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed types of control, such as gestures and language.
- What do you mean?
- We would ask you, for example, to give you this bubble can?
They say it and point to it at the same time.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to tell.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and can’t afford at the time?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the next time we will have to work on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to more accurately record people’s reactions.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they offer a good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What are your demands on modern cameras based on your work with Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is it lacking in resolution, depth or something else?
- The present generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
So all the current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
Not only the resolution along the X and Y axis, but also along the Z axis must be taken into account.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
Human movements are extremely dynamic and frankly stated, the current 30 fps are too little for gestures, especially.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay between 1 and 100 milliseconds in our laboratory in Redmond, where today’s commercial sensors are closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between man and machine.
For my work I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or reinforce the problem, as more calculations would be needed.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera tilts to see how that helps us in the three-dimensional determination of a position.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that when it comes to applying the technology of augmented reality in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it's not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in your hand when you're on the go, but I think the following: The most great variant would be a "changing" extended reality, where we could switch from glasses to smartphone via a cloud,
Glasses are a personal gadget and this is their strength (private ones can only see you), but at the same time also their weakness, because an extended reality through glasses prevents you from being able to work on virtual objects together with others.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is not only accessible to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tangible response!
The hands feel nothing at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures I often talk about the fact that the extended reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently using the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection support.
She perceives pressure excellently!
However, there are also technologies that are actually geared towards giving the "pictures in the air" something hand-fast, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is currently but as weak as someone is pounding over the palms.
There are also wrist bands that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Did you try to trick the brain?
Does it make you think that it feels what it should feel when it sees something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in a closed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms as well as large balls.
So far, the brain can only be moderately outsmarted, and we still have many busy years ahead of us.
This is what makes work in the field of virtual reality so appealing to a researcher: we are only at the beginning of many topics.
