Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth inhabitants on board are on the hunt for a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question is how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
I don’t think there are many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
“It’s Mars and Venus,” says Vladimir Surdin, a research fellow at the Sternberg Astronomical Institute.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees Celsius on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The question of reproduction in space was first addressed by the researchers with regard to the flora.
Half a century earlier, experiments were conducted with plants.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit was not at all different from the earthly species.
This was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to investigate how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
It develops a normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a hold; it has to be able to stand on its legs and start moving," explains Vladimir Sychev, head of the laboratory at the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
Without solid ground, the chicks overwhelmed each other wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not respond to light and sounds.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Twice we hatched chicks and then stopped the whole thing because it is simply impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sychev about the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be found on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized and sent to space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"That was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," says Vladimir Sychev.
After the landing, the space rats were given offspring.
So far, the problem of reproduction directly in space has not been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, humans can do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
Women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was in Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered this question: Can it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally no one answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just a year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The father of the child, Andrijan Nikolaev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawizkaya, who was in orbit twice and even performed work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there remains a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts with whom after long flights everything went well and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is, even in flights in orbit," concludes Kosmonaut Waleri Polyakov, a hero of the Soviet Union and a hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet, humanity must look for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection, and the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydro laboratory in the cosmonaut preparation center is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for work in open space.
The water represents the weightlessness.
Even if adults feel water is pleasant, it is a foreign environment; but infants feel water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders testified that life on land emanated from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is about 9 months in the mother's belly in amniotic fluid, and that it can then become more easily accustomed to water.
In principle, this is logical, since only 2 weeks pass from birth to the first swim.
"It's too little time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenowa.
While for a newborn child, weightlessness is a much more natural state, the woman does not come without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles form enormously quickly and thus also decreases the ability to squeeze out the child.
Well, let's get around this with birth-inducing aids.
The birth could also take place, for example, in a special chamber to squeeze out the child.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Waleri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the earthing, the organism cannot form the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a workout suit in orbit like an adult does for training.
He will simply lack what is of fundamental importance to his life.
“This experiment, which we are conducting together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead us to give birth to a disabled person, a completely unadapted person,” predicts Igor Pestow, head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
Eventually, however, it will become a reality when the Earth inhabitants set out in their spaceships to a distant planet that will become the home for their offspring born in space.
