As far as Czech legislation is concerned, and how important the amendment of the procurement law was to your authority, do you feel any impact?
Considering that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an effect on our examinations.
Since our checks take place later, we have to expect some delay here.
So far, we are more likely to experience effects in the preparatory phase of future controls - for example, we have introduced the new control instrument "detection of risks of uneconomicity" and with it almost 14,000 public contracts are examined and analysed - here the changes will of course have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among others.
Do you see the passage of this law more positively, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be adhered to.
Already under the previous rules, persons subject to examination are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) in such a way that any non-compliance with the procurement law is equivalent to a breach of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have made a form error that does not affect the actual decision-making.
Such a system only puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
First, let’s say which path is not effective.
The prime minister recently said that the SDGs would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system banned or allowed?
A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then it cannot simply come to the head of government, and obstruct the control office, whose duty is to monitor compliance with the law, in its activity.
He can say, “We change the law and allow the thing,” but he can’t say that we pretend to be nothing.
The procurement law contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain operations - and this is also correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, however, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely due to form errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be properly applied - and that is what I think we are missing.
