Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency (ESA) at a meeting of the Council of Ministers, making Poland the second member of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, but they did not always come to terms with it.
I recall here, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s world-renowned contribution to the development of space travel was honored, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the earth-facing side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It has not even been clarified whether the rocket should be used to launch or brake the draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered missiles.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents passed on, it can be seen that the research has advanced to the stage of practical tests.
Research was interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the draft of a photoelectric hunting kite originated from Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the trade press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated at the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society is made in 1954 in the November issue of the journal Problemy, in which four extensive articles are dedicated to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be expected that the exploration of space would have a future.
In its early days in 1956, the Polish space company PTA endeavored to join the International Federation of Spacecraft, which was founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year became the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), Deputy chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch was on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight tests began in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>dów Desert with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The successor to the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B was 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C was 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight altitude for all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aerospace Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after Czech Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek.
Repealing the non-profit law is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on non-profit work.
This decision sparked a lively public discussion.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
The liberal economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause of this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of work (wage), there are price tensions.
This term is understood to mean a situation in which the manufacturer attempts to compete economically by importing favourable goods by "undercutting" competition in order to seize a greater market share and thereby increase its profit.
On a large scale, for most companies, this means moving their production abroad or buying cheaply there, or abandoning their business. The result is high unemployment in countries with similarly high labour costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment caused by it, government expenditure necessarily increases.
This situation is further exacerbated by the fact that entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage caused by them as a whole.
This situation is well known, so concrete statistics are unnecessary at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates in the individual economies a situation in which governments are forced to compete with one another in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus lure foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments deliver their own population to private capital regardless of the social consequences.
This is particularly reflected in amendments to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force the own population to accept the dictate of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done on the one hand by economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, on the other hand by the curtailment of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as increasing differences between rich and poor.
In Germany, there have been public food distribution centres for the poor for several years, who are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regularly cases in which workers receive such a low wage that the state has to increase their income to the minimum of subsistence.
Such a scandal was also uncovered in the case of aid workers employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all of the EU’s southern states will undoubtedly lead to the same state in which people are forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of their social level (as was the case in the 19th century), or to seek a hunger wage on the fringes of society, hoping that private investment capital will eventually flow into the country.
Here naturally the question arises, where does this capital come from?
If it comes from another EU country, only poverty migrates from one country to another; or capital remains the same, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or even in Africa, the workers work for a fraction of the European wages.
This affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media claim to the dismay that the state is not allowed to participate with capital in its own economy, and that planned economy leads to economic catastrophe.
Private capital insists narrowly on its position that the state must not intervene steerably in the economy.
Then, however, one has to wonder whether private capital does not influence politics and thus the entire state in its own egoistic sense.
Here is the clear answer: yes.
