The result is a desperate situation in the field of corruption, mutual prejudice, legislation in which virtually everything is punishable, but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that a State Ministry, due to the lack of finance, commissions private legal firms closely intertwined with the industry to draft legislation.
These bills will then be passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer proceeds from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Apparently the liberal democracies are now quickly in a situation as described by Appian in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic at the time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long been in disintegration, and the offices were occupied with violence.
For lubrication money, by illegally sneaking out advantages, or with stone and sword.
Corruption grew unrestrained, and the people went to the election with already bought votes" ... "People with character did not apply for offices, so that the state had no consul for eight months as a result of this decline" ... "It was really begun to talk about that the only medicine in this difficult situation thought Pompe was a sole domination, and that a strong man had to be elected by the Cäin, then the Cäin all the team...
Today’s society, as in antiquity, is based on the ruthless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital is by its very nature incapable of recognizing and enforcing the advantage for society as a whole.
The result, today as then, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites, who are not in the least striving for deeper reforms.
We must therefore look for the cause of the rise of fascism and communism in the reckless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today’s point of view, the downfall of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause, with the next round already looming.
Particularly catastrophic is the fact that today’s elites face the possible future loss of hundreds of thousands of lives, the humanitarian and social catastrophes we are already witnessing today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history, in complete ignorance.
