The movie Argo: When it's worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had guarded the patronage over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt at hostage-liberation only made it worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages provoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter’s defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover up their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited filming locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by “exfiltration” expert Tony Mendez also required Hollywood’s collaboration.
To make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time, and the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Husaren piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels alternate in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly oversized.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, in the office hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career with this film.
A mocked actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime film Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City Without Grace (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film not to be set in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that set this director’s previous films apart from the Hollywood standard.
Affleck, however, also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, showing the reconstruction of events that have really taken place – the opening sequence of the message’s onslaught is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the sense of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the wrong film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story actually does not offer many scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the few he works quite successfully, where he sometimes helps the reality - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a phone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide spread, which is caused by the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have deserved more space, and they are by no means alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses a bit of traction as a result. It is a film that can be followed with a certain interest and can taste the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70s.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day in a certain way, and as proof of how far-reaching the notions of the omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services are, it is sufficient.
