The MVRDV architects prove that the true adventures are not only in the mind - on the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built book mountain - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by by the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician in a nearby large company, says: "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder what we still need a library for today.
All have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one volunteers to go to one of these old-style libraries today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy city just outside the gates of Rotterdam, is an odd record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant community has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to the general education and to recreate the seven fictional bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as beautifully painted reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library must be here!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam-based architectural firm MVRDV, master of daring beam diagrams and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took up the matter with familiar serenity and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury was still gazing around and shrugging, the naughty Maas piled up his exquisite contribution to the size of a pyramid and ended his shareholder-backed speech with the words: "Dear City!"
So this is him, my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30-million-euro mountain was dumped.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the faceless small town retort, which until now had no more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian area and an astonishingly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory, in order to make a piece of contemporary architecture richer.
Above all, however, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression: bookeldorado under a cheese bell.
There is a lift in the middle of the mountain massif, but the true pleasures of space and reading can be discovered by climbing the topography on foot.
The all-glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lamps unmistakably speak the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
They are already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Normally, the bookcases stand along the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, and in the middle lies a large, dark room, which is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and pushed the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the book mountain is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and home technology center.
A special pleasure are the black bookcases, which are sometimes wall covering, sometimes parapet, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, tactics and smell are foreign.
Even inclined architects and civil engineers shake their heads because of the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycling materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the Spijkenisse municipality, at the request of the Standard.
And so one day, in a Friesland farm, we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years, a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used in the Netherlands as a root support in greenhouses and fields.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for bulky garbage.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in these quantities - to plates four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells like a new car and a sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-metre-long hike, the Literaturcafé not only rewards you with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and stuffed ficus trees.
They ensure the atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a flagship project in terms of ecology," says Troubort.
It is heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the book mountain is under a glass fall, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly inside.
The wide wooden glue binders, which stand transverse to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, serve as shade and capture much of the sunlight.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done with fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, was already daring to enter the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: For the opening a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from his personal stock.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the not yet fully stocked library – currently 70,000 pieces – will be filled.
The concept has emerged.
The shelves are filled to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
“I think, thanks to our invitation, now every resident has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for decoration.
With this, MVRDV has succeeded in that royal discipline, which is called in the technical jargon identity foundation.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as he may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the request for observer status of the Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence – but without being too critical of Israel.
During the Libyan uprising in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is currently transforming its foreign policy away from a policy that was managed by the US, so to speak, to a German foreign policy.
What makes it more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still tackling their role, but they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as France or the United Kingdom.
What does a “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows a willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are to a certain degree different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests had an impact on the attitude towards the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be cautious not to confront the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
It definitely plays a role.
But I wouldn’t want to put too much weight on it either, it’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it definitely plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great deal of understanding in Europe and even in the United States of America for the German position.
Therefore, I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect.
