These courts served during Mubarak’s rule to suppress oppositionists.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were in military custody.
The state should also, according to the draft, “protect the true nature of the Egyptian family and promote its morality and values.”
This is legally so blurred that state institutions could even control the content of film art and literature with the help of this article.
In plain language, this means nothing but censorship.
By the way, no article explicitly states the equality of men and women.
For this, another forbids offending or slandering the Prophet Muhammad and his messengers.
But what is an insult and how it should be punished remains unclear.
Equally dubious is the wording that “insulting people” is prohibited.
Is a caricature of the president or a joke enough at the expense of a lawyer?
The matter of interpretation, like so much in the draft, which Morsi has for signature and, according to his words, "very soon" will be presented to the Egyptians for the popular vote.
"The revolution is back"
The opposition has been forming for weeks against the supremacy of the Islamists.
Tens of thousands gathered in unusual agreement on Friday evening in Tahrir Square in Cairo and vowed to bring down the Charter even before it could enter into force.
“The revolution has returned and we will win,” said Hamdin Sabbahi, third-placed in the presidential election.
The Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed El-Baradei, said the draft constitution belongs "on the rubbish mountain of history".
Via Twitter, he accused Mursi’s supporters of wanting to lead a “coup against democracy.”
“If he calls the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him,” said opposition leader Jasser Said.
“We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been atoned,” Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali as saying.
And several judges announced that they would not want to monitor the referendum, which would render it invalid.
"The Qur'an is our Constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, for its part, blew to the counter-demonstration, but as a precaution not in Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other side of the Nile in front of the Cairo University.
Many veiled women and followers of the Salafists took part, shouting, "The people demand the application of God's law."
They demanded from Mursi, “Clean up the land!” and asserted, “The Qur’an is our constitution.”
A struggle for sovereignty over the symbolic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would probably have evoked civil war-like conditions.
Obviously, Mursi’s supporters did not want to risk that.
The Muslim Brotherhood declared that both opponents of the draft constitution and supporters had spoken out loud and clearly.
Now is the time to let the people at the ballot box decide in which direction the country should go.
A majority for the draft of the Islamists is considered safe.
"The word 'human rights' doesn't even come up"
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry at this forced constitutional process, which should have been going until February and should have involved all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were in prison or on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, convicted, imprisoned.
"And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution," he complains in a conversation with the "World on Sunday".
Morsi’s expansion of power to all three powers in the state resigned the lawyer.
These measures are blatant violations of democratic rules of the game and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
“Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto puts it out of place,” Saeda said.
But without civil society organizations, a democracy cannot function.
Saeda feels left alone, even by the international community, which considers the ideological directional struggle on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
That could be revenge.
A protester on the Tahrir warns, “You are giving birth to a monster that you can no longer control.”
Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most foul-smelling fish in the world?
Norway’s five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest living standards – not only in Europe, but around the world.
Could the country’s secret to success have anything to do with the local appetite for pretty bad-smelling fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, damp sportswear.
And leave her there for a week.
You have to imagine the nose-stunning smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to go away.
Rakfisk is salt-sprinkled trout, which - depending on how smelly you would like your fish - is fermented in water for up to a year.
When the darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, now, really very captivating specialty.
