Even from Sweden, the old rival, who not too long ago was far richer than Norway, immigrants flock.
Rakfisk is seen as something important - an essential, albeit rigorous, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the most expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t make it to the world press often, and most people don’t seem to bother with it.
Here one still hates to name Anders Breivik by name - those racist right-wing extremists who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, it refers only to the “July 22 incident”.
Norwegians find it hard to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Mainly responsible for Norway’s wealth today has been the growth of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries since the early 1970s.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays with ripe Rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and sharp blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Your English is just like that of most people here.
We're not very empathetic, we don't like boasting.
Norway has been very cautious with its oil wealth - a large part of the industry's revenues are invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the global economic crisis, everyone threw around with money they did not have, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And of course eat Rakfisk," she adds with carefree laughter.
I stand in the snow and stand for another dish - from Rakfisk I have had enough.
Such a moose burger is definitely something else. The juicy meat mouths me.
But in the evening the stinkfish is again on the menu.
The hotel I’m staying at is one of several venues that organize a Rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best – or perhaps the most challenging sense of smell – fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates of Rakfisk.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
You clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by aquavit.
But maybe it's the severe haze of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start
As Mexico’s future President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares for his inauguration, BBC’s Will Grant analyzes the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly poor.
Even on better days, this is an ever-clogged city, but on Monday a steel ring was erected that blocks several important traffic routes to the capital and causes chaos on the streets.
The aim, however, was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new President Enrique Pena Nieto will take over the leadership of the nation.
He is faced with a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has proved economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already claimed 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My administration is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country surrounding the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built and which are a great improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with his name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and ongoing changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who serves as a congressman for the party Pena Nietos, which works for PRI.
In particular, as far as security and the economy are concerned, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so urgently needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has set great expectations for Enrique Pena Nieto.
The accusations of the opposition, which the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was deployed to fight drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
The bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left in the last two years alone on a patch of wasteland near a large landfill.
More than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico during Governor Pena Nieto’s tenure, a statistic that even exceeds that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and murders of innocent women.
Critics Pena Nietos believe that he at least did not adequately address the issue of women’s killings during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the run-down neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes that she was murdered by her partner.
“When I arrived at her house, it seemed as if her body had been washed,” recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the body stiffness had already been used.
As her mother tells her story, from the wall a picture of Mariana looks down on us. It is attached next to a cross that carries a single word: Justice.
But this, so the family, has been denied to her so far.
The authorities treated me as if I were a gossip, a troublemaker, a scolder.
They just want to accept their judgment and keep their mouths shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and omissions,” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the Presidential Binding on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his term.
“I hope that as president he will be the way he was as governor,” says the PRI congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that is exactly what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Prosecutors say Bradley Manning did not complain about abuse
Prosecutors Contrary to Bradley Manning’s Allegation of Being Abused in Prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time at the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a dismissal of the indictment due to harsh conditions of detention
U.S. Army Freedman Accused of Stealing Thousands of Confidential Documents
Prosecutors on Friday tried to determine that Army-backed Bradley Manning — accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history — missed several opportunities to complain about the alleged mistreatment he suffered in military custody.
At a cross-examination of Mannings during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, had no complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to dismiss the indictment - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard time in prison - Manning had testified that he had considered the suicide in prison.
The U.S. military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his time in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning passed through the forms that officials had filled out after meeting Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he had been held under heightened conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officials asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein interviewed him on Friday about the forms, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards as “excellent” and the treatment by the facility as a whole as “very professional.”
The forms, according to Fein, contained no complaints about abuse, although officials had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them, but that they had not been recorded.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) 'No problems', and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to examine the suicidal thoughts he mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to lower his observation status to "prevent injury."
The military said it assigned him this restrictive status — which is one level under suicidal risk — for his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and get rid of the observational status for injury prevention ... to be able to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning said Thursday he was arrested and transferred to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had once become unconscious due to the heat.
Not knowing what is going on with him or in the outside world has been distressing.
“My world was shrinking on Camp Arafjon, on this cage,” Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours — and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and glasses.
Manning said he had tried to stay in motion because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even to lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards could no longer see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - for example, he slept naked in his cell in Quantico one night and had to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
At the interrogation on Friday, Manning said he had shut down the blanket he could have covered himself with on an order from his guard, but he admitted that no one had asked him to.
On Thursday, Manning said he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, trying to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his detention experiences and drastically reduce his length of detention should he be sentenced at his trial in the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offenses, while other charges that are considered too extreme are to be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained under the regulations that apply to all inmates held under the highest security measures in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawful publication of intelligence information on the Internet, transfer of national defense information, and theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he faces life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of chances
Mexicans tend to blame emigrants - they remind them of hard times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when inconsistency spread in me.
Signs referred to two queues: one for "Mexicans" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure which one I should go to.
I grew up in Central California and was called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just like my friends in Boston call themselves "Irene" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italian".
Later, I chose “Mexican-American.”
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home there was no need for shortcuts or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in that language at both ends of an interview.
But I do not have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I also do not get rid of my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and lined up for aliens.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those issues that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans nowadays are just as likely to stay in Mexico as they are to emigrate to the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico’s war against the drug cartels, even though he did not give details in this regard.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country’s preserving gun leadership to give them more than half of their territory.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the mildest criticism of Mexico, you hear complaints in the Mexican press and among the country’s elites about how Americans are oppressing the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma set out on the path of war.
And yet, Mexico’s biggest challenge in truth lies in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, one person — perhaps a parent or grandparent — didn’t get a chance in Mexico and emigrated northwards.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty goes to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may now have lived the American dream, attended good schools, and got good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we are living — not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership don’t like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have left.
And then we wouldn't be trapped behind the silk curtain now - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans dislike them.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel that they belong neither to one country nor to the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is rooted in none of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: Some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to resume their ties to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional “ambassadors” for Mexico who represent their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great it is to visit this country and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify its ties with Mexico.
Well, now.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unjust distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge at how their family members were treated not so long ago.
- Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to stifle such hope in the bud.
Amid the usual accusations, countless buildings have been laid to shreds, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed – and for the first time rockets have been struck from Gaza near Israel’s Tel Aviv metropolis and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not – Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this turmoil.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there is reason to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism in view of the current situation seems anything but appropriate.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened the hard-boiled on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, even though its group itself suffered major losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are invaded in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, temperate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders may conclude that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a rejuvenating regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken sides with Hamas – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Rejoicing Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist imprint could face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt - by far the most populous and most important Arab country - on the southern flank of Israel has changed the balance of the region in a lasting way.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his overthrow in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is consorted with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor who cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome", has proved itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while Israel will be able to sleep more calmly.
In diplomatic terms, the United States remains steadfast in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers – not least thanks to the blockades that have flowed into the West Bank and thus into the main part of any Palestinian state. These protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared to be in violation of international law.
Netanyahu is doing well. His Likud party has allied itself with an even more militant group ahead of the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these insidious Palestinians coddle and leave them a state of their own?
If they actually had control over the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire rockets just like their fellow Gazans?
No, it is better to keep them behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Maybe the hardliners will be able to win, but the Arab spring could make a cut through the bill.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense status is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments in restoring their economy.
That pragmatic President Morsi teamed up with Barack Obama to reach a truce could be a promising sign — and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratization, Palestinians are still being deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder keg that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli-occupied areas, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to repress Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside.
The correct answer is that represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and this newspaper: two states where Israel is ceding territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence in enforcing this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms deliveries to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by exchanges of territory and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also move Hamas and Fatah to an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama, too, has to help move Israel to negotiations.
During his first term in office, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he is equally reluctant to participate.
But this is an unfortunate, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a substantial interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws for uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging laws have entered into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colors with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and images, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font, is from next Saturday.
Australia introduces the world’s most stringent tobacco packaging regulations.
The Australian government wants to stop young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
Studies have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at age 26 are 99% more likely to not start smoking thereafter.
"You can see even in young children that they understand the message of trying to promote tobacco companies with their brand image," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a minor impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws favoured black market trade, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the unbearable packaging has risen enormously since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco two months ago at the top Australian court with their challenge to the law.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units at wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
For us, this is a good deal.
According to experts, the catch lies in the popularity of social media among precisely the population that the plan is aimed at.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, barred them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most merchants to stop interpreting cigarettes in stores.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising through local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Those who market tobacco and have only a small area left to promote their products don’t get around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a health researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook, Freeman has noted an increase in brand experience reports written by “all-normal people.”
You have to ask yourself: is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that they even record a video for it - or is a marketing agency involved with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry instead of marketing is focusing on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations - those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, although none of the countries trade larger with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to provide photographic warnings in 2001.
In the meantime, these have been expanded to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures do not affect me.
I just ignore them.
"You just take a tip and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box with a photo of a mouth tumor printed on it.
Honestly, there's only one reason I'd stop, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the “King of the Pack” tobacco trade in downtown Sydney, says uniform packaging has made it difficult to replenish his shelves.
“I used to take an hour to sort a delivery, now I need four,” Yu says.
“The government should have just banned cigarettes altogether – then we would have said to ourselves, okay, that’s it, we’re shutting down,” he adds visibly angry.
In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored, too.
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane went down due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to get bored with a few thoughts.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty annoying – even when books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts refer to boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us — and our children — to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thoughts, which may encourage creativity.
And because most of us nowadays are almost constantly staring at one screen or another, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
Should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Oh, yeah.
No, no, no.
I'll come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011), doesn’t think so.
“In fact, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
The walls of Pompeii adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom that dates back to the first century.
And then there’s the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and presenting the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfying job but not being able to do it."
Boredom therefore differs from apathy in that the person is not busy but wants to be.
With apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a "disturbance of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and a feeling that time is slowly passing".
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re boring, even if we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a band in front of a person's article in front of a magazine.
Some groups listened to a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content; others listened to it at low volume, so it was hardly noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who listened to the barely audible television reported feeling more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, couldn't find a reason for them, and attributed their troubles to boredom.
If you try to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, if you perform a monotonous activity - "like looking for defective products on a factory conveyor belt, it can distract music and help you not feel bored."
In fact, he says, we now know that rummage and scribbles, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even combat them by keeping people more physically attentive.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to hoard around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” Professor Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a roaring loudspeaker, a particularly tiring movie.
But some people get bored easier than others.
To measure these differences, researchers in the 1980s developed a "scala for boredom susceptibility".
On the scale are statements like “Many things I have to do are repeating and are monotonous” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have enough time for everything”.
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys become boring more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - especially when it comes to the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of teens were bored at school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were out of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is certain that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have a great influence on their daily routine.
So back to my origin question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to alleviate them - studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors are studying the relationship between boredom and creativity, which is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been exploring the subject for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
If you’re bored and you use that energy to play the guitar and cook it, you’ll be happy.
But television can provide feelings of happiness in the short term, but these disappear in the long term.
If you give your bored child an iPad, it can take him away from boredom, but he has not learned to talk or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: “Self-control is transferred from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to talk, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we be too critical of them.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even away from the constant sprinkling of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the tormenting, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to shut down and relax.
“In an environment where we are constantly being overstimulated, it’s hard to get busy once the noise is muted.”
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old community college student and football player, is on trial in southeastern Colorado for a misdemeanor that will soon be legal in that state: the possession of fewer marijuana bouquets and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving a car in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was summoned for possession of drugs and drug utensils — cavalry offenses, each with a $100 penalty — and received a court appointment.
“We are treated like criminals,” Orozco said.
But is he also one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for its own use, the response to hundreds of smaller drug offenses depends less on the law than on location.
Hundreds of legal violations revolving around marijuana have already been dropped here and in Washington State, which has approved similar measures.
Police authorities no longer prosecute adults over the age of 21 for possession to a small extent. This will be permitted by law as soon as the new laws enter into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado’s more conservative districts have announced they will continue to track existing marijuana offenses and still cite people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
"This situation is evolving so fast that I don't know what's going to happen next," said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
And regulators in the state of Washington are scratching their heads.
They are awaiting guidance on the establishment of a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - with a deadline of 1 December 2013 in mind.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is ahead of most states in terms of marijuana regulation, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well suited for guidance," said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Spirits Authority.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
“We don’t have a real precedent we can follow,” he adds.
The Washington law, called I-502, comes into force on December 6, and thus also forms the end point of a gray zone in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but ownership is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified during this time - such as how to agree on the state's requirement of "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with the prohibition of cannabis shops within 300 meters around schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
“Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the metropolitan area of Seattle,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On Nov. 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his Aurora employees stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses in people over the age of 21, and that the police would “immediately” not pursue criminal charges for these offenses.
Chief Oates added that police will continue to enforce urban regulations regulating medical marijuana growers and continue to prosecute drug traffickers.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck has a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his authority would continue to prosecute cases of marijuana possession, mainly to encourage consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people must be held accountable for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana in court, although many have also been charged with other offences.
"Our authority has a duty to prosecute violations that were crimes at the time of the crime," Buck said in a statement.
Reactions are mixed even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, no longer report adults for possession of smaller quantities.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending possession proceedings.
“I don’t think I’m wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes,” he says.
Although 55% of voters in Colorado supported the measure, it was clear from the start that it would not be easy to reconcile personal marijuana consumption with the complexities of government and legal system.
And the contradictory reactions throughout the state brought to light a profound quarrel among local officials with regard to the great green experiment.
District attorneys are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents defendants in court for marijuana offenses and acts on-site as a spokesperson for the National Marijuana Reform Organization.
“They have spent so much of their lives prosecuting people for being unable to accept legalization,” he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are treated as national examples of drug legalization.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an era of legal sale, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which will continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a crime.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Justice Department will give in.
Despite several eye-catching arrests of medical marijuana consumers and sellers, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while criminal officers are unlikely to enter doors to seize smaller amounts of drugs, they are likely to be reluctant to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana businesses under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not even waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before election day, some local community administrations approved moratoriums for new marijuana businesses, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, passed a six-month ban, likely to be passed next week.
“We don’t want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at the federal level,” said City Council member Bob Nicholson.
Our community voted against this change of law.
We are guided by what the community has decided, not by what the state has decided.
Many questions are still open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
It’s not just university students today who are attacked for their views.
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at the University of Oxford.
Both my father and older brother had attended that university, which I once thought was the greatest temple of knowledge in the world, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization – free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my arrival at Worscester College at the end of the eighties – where I had planned to study history – I had packed my bags again, bringing about the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the neighboring room.
Author A N Wilson mischievously declared that I had left university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, it ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had only been bullied for one reason – one reason that seemed all the more narrow-minded and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: My late father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a proponent of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate right-wing students is suffering from similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for the same equal rights protection that benefits gays, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable" because of their political views.
They are calling for a seat on their college’s Equality Committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Their situation was exacerbated by a recently aired documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
It featured, among others, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of Oxford University’s Conservative Student Association, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and sparred in a silver-coloured suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are seen as “sin heaps for the introduction of higher tuition fees.”
The 20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the University of Nottingham’s Conservative Student Association, said in a Sunday newspaper: “There is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
“People think we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other.”
Samuel Roberts, 21 and history student at Corpus Christi, who initiated the plea for greater protection, believes such a climate is “unpleasant.” 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-elect of the Oxford Conservative Student Association, says she has observed a growing rejection of moderate right students among JCR members.
“This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and the well-being of members,” she says.
In my first weeks at Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to award an honorary degree to Margaret Thatcher - a former student - due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have scared even Stalinists.
In the first days of the first-semester week, when new students got to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of what would happen in the future.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even participated with joy.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the wooden-paneled rooms of the tutoring.
At my first of these events, I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English, but I was not prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (who has since passed away), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled upon it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite ugly.
“Do Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?” he asked me.
The other students giggled.
In my eyes there were tears.
“I suggest that they take a few French hours in their spare time – so if you’re not too busy with your social activities,” Pitt grumbled at me.
I went back to my room with my head hanging.
That evening, I was sitting alone in college at dinner, when someone gently tipped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it's how it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is being harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be worse for you.
Most Tory first semesters claim to be supporters of the Labour Party.
At a local pub, I tried to dress up later.
I insisted that I did not agree on all points with Mrs. Thatcher.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
An undergraduate in philosophy, politics, and economics who had ironically attended Eton College, which is considered to be conservative, told me, “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.”
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They beat each other, don't they?
I felt like homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years before me stretched before my spiritual eye into a purgatory of rejection and isolation.
The only tutor to openly acknowledge himself as Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who was based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for his Marxist-determinist perspective of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at the University of Bilkent in Ankara, Turkey.
“You won’t be happy here,” he told me.
I started commuting between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed unbelieving.
During his time in the forties, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said quietly.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreaming tower tops.
Even my communist friends always showed impeccable manners.
His damp eyes were clouded.
Give the whole thing a chance.
I'm sure you're just being teased.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance became weaker.
One of my male friends, also a Tory supporter, had given up on the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, where another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Although I secretly collapsed in shame, I admitted that my parents had “brainwashed” me and called them “old fools.”
The relief lasted only briefly.
It was my father who punched the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch Press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my harasser gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You're welcome to call me a weeping slut.
But no 18-year-old should ever suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory Prime Ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to celebrity"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino - Master of Couture", which opened this week in London, ABC speaks with Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous customers of the Italian fashion maker.
Somerset House, the former residence of Isabel I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
This was acknowledged by the designer at the opening of "Valentino - Master of Couture", a grand retrospective for which more than 130 haute couture dresses have been compiled, created by his "Maison" over the last 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says with his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition is the conclusion of a story whose only protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clientele.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the stuffy and distant world of nobility.
