The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and their health at risk when they carry 70 kilos of sulphur along the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 mine workers who make a living by extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he must climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphur-containing gas emanating from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones that can weigh up to 70 kilograms in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the rugged stone paths.
Although it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2,386 meters, the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the ascent at turtle pace, keeping the balance and taking their steps carefully so that they do not slip out and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed down the slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 Eurocent for every kilo of sulphur they mine.
Arriving at the top, they pave the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiresomely heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and (never better said) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilogram of sulphur.
They then sell it for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocent) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we usually carry 70 kg, we receive about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who usually makes three routes a day.
For each track he needs three hours, after which he is completely managed, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
But what looks like a miserable reward for such an almost inhuman effort is three times what he would earn from fieldwork.
"The daily salary of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day during the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros) is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees a day, and the work was not that hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason as important in Indonesia as the sulphur: "I converted a girl from Bali where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life at Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulphur has already left its first traces on him, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
"I'm going to work here for two more years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man, punished by life, could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and stands up every morning at two o’clock because the sulphur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets with sulphur on their shoulders on the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur mining to save costs, and does not supply any equipment to carriers who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera that the guardians of this nature park demand, together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrycot.
"This work is for the animals and not for man," protests Madrusin, a stubborn 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as possible" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Even if the sulphur burns the throat and itches the eyes, when the wind suddenly turns and the mineworkers jam into the thick columns that rise from the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains about serious diseases ... of course, except for the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders, which are shaped by the weight of the bait.
With the basket on his back, Unainik is only able to carry 50 kg at the age of 53.
Every day he and his companions break 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks via a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari at a distance of 18 kilometers.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, with some teeth missing.
Of his five children, the elder at the age of 30 also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time goes by, but the poverty continues generation after generation in one of the toughest professions in the world: those who work as human burdens on the Kawah Ijen.
