Conclusion of the Summit of the Unasur without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and theoretically to be signed by the seven present rulers.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources in the Chancellery of State and President initially said that they would hand it over after the exam, but later stated that it would be published on the website of the Peruvian government at some time.
When asked about the text, they said that the contents were explained by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists’ access to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private meeting, limited audio".
The little information circulating among the journalists was received by the press representatives of some of the UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press officer.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from different national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the Peruvian presidential office sent an e-mail to the media with the "concluding statement" of the summit, but it was the Humala declaration and not the official document at the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit South America-Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite a press appeal, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was not published.
The official website of ASPA confirms that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems for journalists were in place, but they limited access to information to a large extent.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague resolving a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which begins in The Hague on Monday, in the process that Lima initiated against Santiago to hear the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we presently bring to this international court," Humala said.
“Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that abides by international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, makes agreements, and submits to international courts,” Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era added, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the IGH came after Colombia filed a lawsuit against the Bogotá agreement, which agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua that it considered a serious mistake.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from UNASUR since the ousting of its president Fernando Lugo in 2011, did not attend the meeting.
President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The head of state read the final document, in which he announced that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for an investment amount of a total of 17 billion dollars.
On the decisions taken, he said that UNASUR countries will “take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we extend the decisions on residency rights.”
He said action would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organized, transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters."
With the crisis in Europe, “economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant traits, but should serve to expand our output and show our peoples a better future,” Humala added.
“We have decided to prioritize a number of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America, and especially in rural and border areas ... and thus uniting our countries and opening up new economic forms,” the Peruvian president said in a read-out statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvians, lying on the transverse axes of his territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which should ensure a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its re-establishment in the Union of South American Nations," he said.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting in Mexico on Saturday with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict respectfully after a judgment of the IGH questioned by Bogotá.
“Maybe I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow,” Santos said.
“We will review all of these paths – they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary,” he said.
“I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectfully as possible,” Santos said.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to attend the takeover of the country’s new president, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
As part of the summit, the bloc’s defence ministers also met in advance to adopt the 2013 action plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru is the temporary chair of the regional bloc.
